    "## How to use\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "from benchmark_data_loader import load_subject\n",
    "from benchmark_analysis import estimate_pia_surface_image_autoselect\n",
    "\n",
    "s = load_subject('755252')\n",
    "surface, info, scores = estimate_pia_surface_image_autoselect(s)\n",
    "\n",
    "# surface  → quadratic dict {a, b, c, p, q, r, ...}\n",
    "# info     → {'selected': 'mid488_tq0.85', 'used_channels': ['488', '514'], ...}\n",
    "# scores   → DataFrame of all candidates with Q / Qcon_n / pass / selected\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "## Key design notes & caveats\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Why two metrics.**  `Q` (median below-surface brightness) discriminates pia from gap but fails to reject deep-in-tissue surfaces.  `Qcon_n` (normalised above/below contrast) rejects deep surfaces but cannot rank real-pia candidates.  Their combination is both necessary and sufficient on 6 subjects.\n",
    "- **Distribution-driven threshold.**  The 0.9 cut on `Qcon_n` was chosen because on this 6-subject benchmark real-pia candidates land at ≥ 0.98 and tissue-body candidates at ≤ 0.55 — a > 0.4 gap with no candidates in between.  Any threshold in [0.6, 0.97] would produce identical selections; 0.9 is the centre of the valley.  If future data lives in that gap, the threshold should be re-picked from the bimodal distribution (per the session-global rule on thresholds).\n",
    "- **Soft bias toward deeper pia.**  `argmax Q` prefers the deepest candidate among pia-pass survivors because tissue brightness monotonically increases with depth in the 10–50 µm window.  On 790322 this nudges the selection ~16 µm below N22 (above_frac 1.13 % instead of 0.07 %).  Still well within gates, but worth noting if we later demand tighter control (e.g. GFP surfaces).\n",
    "- **AF-carrying channels are subject-specific.**  The \"right\" channel subset varies: 755252 wants `488+514` (drop AF-heavy 405 & 594), 767018 wants `594-only`, 782149/788406 want `488+mid+594` (drop 405).  Auto-select handles this without needing per-subject hand-tuning.\n",
